com.quest.glue.api.services
Interface ThreadFactoryService

All Superinterfaces:
Service
public interface ThreadFactoryService
extends Service

This service provides ThreadFactory instances that allow agents to safely create threads. These threads are managed by FglAM so their classloaders are correctly initialized and will not leak when the agent is destroyed. In addition, all the threads will be placed into the same group and associated with the agent itself to simplify debugging thread dumps.

Agents are encouraged to use these FglAM provided factories over their own when creating thread-pool type objects like executors. Using a factory from FglAM gives agents the flexibility to create whatever type of pool is appropriate for their requirements while still allowing FglAM to have some insight and (when necessary) control over what the threads are doing.

The following example illustrates how an agent implementation would use this service when creating a thread pool. All the threads in the pool will be tracked by FglAM, but the parameters governing how that pool is used will remain up to the agent. 

 ThreadFactoryService factoryService = ...
 ThreadFactory factory = factoryService.createFactory();
 ExecutorService executor = Executors.newCachedThreadPool(factory);
The new executor is a plain Java executor and does not require any FglAM-specific knowledge to use. Agents are free to submit tasks, shut down, and perform whatever operations they require on it without requiring any further API calls from FglAM. The only difference is that FglAM is aware of the threads and is able to properly interrupt, destroy, or otherwise clean them up when the agent has been destroyed.

Note: Threads created by this service that execute agent code do not make use of the locking mechanism used by other FglAM services. That is, code that is executed by a thread created using one of these factories can execute in parallel to code in an agents destroy, stopDataCollection, or other lifecycle API methods. In that regard they behave identically to threads created directly from within the agent.

Since:
5.6.2

createFactory

java.util.concurrent.ThreadFactory createFactory(java.lang.String groupName)
Return a factory that will create new threads in a new thread group groupName and apply the default thread parameters to them.

If null is provided for groupName this method is functionally equivalent to createFactory().

Returns:
A thread factory initialized using default values
See Also:
DEFAULT_PRIORITY, DEFAULT_DAEMON

createFactory

java.util.concurrent.ThreadFactory createFactory(java.lang.String groupName,
                                                 int priority,
                                                 boolean daemon)
Create a factory that returns threads with customized properties. If the groupName parameter is null then new threads will be placed into the agent's default thread group. Otherwise a new child of the agent's default group will be created for new threads to be placed in.

Agents are encouraged to use default settings as much as possible. They have been selected to ensure that agent threads to not starve each other or otherwise negatively effect the FglAM environment as a whole. This method is provided to support the rare situations where the default settings are insufficient.

Parameters:
groupName - The name of the thread group to place new threads in or null to place them in the agent's default group
priority - The priority level for threads created by this factory
daemon - Whether the factory should create daemon threads or not
Returns:
A thread factory initialized using the provided values
See Also:
DEFAULT_PRIORITY, DEFAULT_DAEMON

newThread

java.lang.Thread newThread(java.lang.Runnable runnable)
A convenience method to create a single thread that runs an runnable object. This method is functionally equivalent to the following: 
 Runnable runnable = ...;

 ThreadFactoryService factoryService = ...
 ThreadFactory factory = factoryService.createFactory();

 Thread t = factory.newThread( runnable );

Note that this thread does not participate in FglAM's agent locking mechanism, meaning that this thread will continue running even during an agent lifecycle method such as destroy. Whenever possible agent developers are strongly encouraged to avoid threads such as this to ensure agents remain in a consistent state. For most situations using ExecutorFactoryService.newThread(Runnable) is preferred to create threads that do participate in agent locking.

Parameters:
runnable - The object that will be run by the new thread
Returns:
A new thread that will execute runnable
